To terminate a C program, you can use the `exit()` function from the `stdlib.h` library. This function takes an integer argument, which represents the exit status of the program. The `exit()` function is declared as follows:

```c
void exit(int status);
```

To use the `exit()` function, you need to include the `stdlib.h` header file in your program. Here's an example of how to use the `exit()` function to terminate a C program:

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // Your program code here

    // Terminating the program
    exit(EXIT_SUCCESS); // or any other status code

    // This line will not be executed
    printf("Program should have terminated by now.\n");

    return 0;
}
```

In the example above, the `exit()` function is called with the `EXIT_SUCCESS` status code, which indicates a successful program termination. You can replace `EXIT_SUCCESS` with any other status code you want. The `exit()` function will terminate the program immediately, and the program will not execute any further code after the `exit()` call.

Note that the `exit()` function does not return a value to the calling process. It only terminates the program with the specified exit status.

